  <p>
    <alert>Definition 4</alert>
    An <em>event</em> is a subset of a sample space of an experiment.
    A <em>probability</em> is a value assigned to a set of outcomes for an experiment (an event).
    The probability of an event represents the likelihood that one of the outcomes
    in the set will occur during the experiment.
  </p>
  <p>
    <row><alert>Example</alert></row>
    1.
    We roll a red six-sided die and a blue six-sided die and note the result of each roll.
    Find the sample space of the experiment and identify the outcomes in the events
    <me>E=\text{ the red die shows }3</me> and 
    <me>F=\text{ the sum of the results is 5.}</me>
  </p>

  <figure>
    <image source="https://drive.google.com/uc?export=view&id=146yE8Qb7SA0ylzbhmMjVx3f6XlN1B6N9" width="700px" description="Tree Diagram of Experiment" />
    <caption>
      Tree diagram for rolling a red die then blue die.
    </caption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    Then
    <me>E = \{R3B1,R3B2,R3B3,R3B4,R3B5,R3B6\}</me>
    and 
    <me>F = \{R1B4,R2B3,R3B2,R4B1\},</me>
    so we can see that <m>|E|=6</m> and <m>|F|=4</m> (where we use the notation absolute value of a set to represent the size of the set).
  </p>

  <p>
    <alert>Definition 5</alert>
    Let us say that we have an experiment with exactly three outcomes: 1, 2, and 3.
    Suppose we perform the experiment <m>n</m> times and outcome 1 occurs <m>n_1</m> times,
    outcome 2 occurs <m>n_2</m> times, and outcome 3 occurs <m>n_3</m> times.
    Then <m>n_1 + n_2 + n_3 = n</m>.
    In this case, the <em>relative frequency</em> of outcome 1 is <m>\frac{n_1}{n}</m>,
    of outcome 2 is <m>\frac{n_2}{n}</m>, and of outcome 3 is <m>\frac{n_3}{n}</m>.
    Using these frequencies to measure the likelihood that an outcome occurs, notice two
    important properties.
    <ul>
      <li>1. Each frequency is between 0 and 1, and</li>
      <li>2. The sum of all frequencies is equal to 1.</li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  <p>
    Remark, in general, you can look at arbitrary probability spaces, but events still have to follow these two rules.
    However, for the core material in Math 5248, the two above will be sufficient to describe the types of 
    probabiliy experiments we'll be interested in.
  </p>
  <p>
    <alert>Definition 6</alert>
    Suppose that we are given an experiment with sample space <m>S</m> and 
    every outcome is equally likely to occur. For any event <m>E\subset S</m>,
    the <em>probability of Event <m>E</m></em>, denoted 
    <me>\mathscr P(E) = \frac{|E|}{|S|},</me>
    which <alert>only</alert> works when every outcome is equally likely.
    More generally, the probability of event <m>E</m> is the sum of the probabilities of the outcomes contained in the set <m>E</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    <alert>Remark</alert>
    In class, we'll use tree diagrams to develop conditional probabilities and discuss
    the general case when every outcome is not equally likely. However, for the purposes
    of what we need to do in order to attack classical ciphers, the previous page along 
    with the material above is sufficient.
  </p>

  <p>
    <alert>You practice</alert>
    A few practice problems in order to gauge your understanding of the previous
    material. We assume the die in question are <em>fair</em> (meaning every number is equally likely, no weighted dice to rig the game here).
  </p>
